## What changed in this version\
\
Three upgrades landed from the comparison. The `VISION.md` template gained grounding fields it was missing \'97 Core Problem, Intended Solution, Target Users, Core Principles & Constraints, and High-Level Architecture \'97 so an agent has more to reason from. The bootstrap mode now selects a vision *style* (minimal, product, guardrail, or narrative) based on the project type it detects, rather than forcing one shape onto every project. And we explicitly kept the discipline that's ours: churning status and task lists stay in `LOOP_STATE.md`, so `VISION.md` remains a stable constitution rather than a noisy mix of principle and to-do.\
\
Everything else \'97 the two-mode skill, the agnostic config split, the parallel multi-agent orchestration with the maker/checker separation, and the human checkpoints \'97 carries over unchanged. The two responsibilities that stay yours on every project are the same as before: set `parallelism` by your real review bandwidth, and keep `VISION.md` current, because the loop will faithfully drive toward whatever's written there.\
\
This is now a complete, self-contained reference you can copy into any repo. If you give me one real project \'97 its stack, test command, and the tool you'll run it in \'97 I can fill in `loop.config.yml`, `agent.config.yml`, and a first-draft `VISION.md` in the right style so you have a working instance instead of a template.}